We have imbalanced classes. The positive class (represented by 1, ie, customer did leave) is the minority class. Due to absense of problem statement, we'll assume that its more important we don't miss the ones who will leave the bank. So, the metric to focus on here is recall.

def data_preprocessor(df):
    df = df.drop('customer_id',axis=1)
    df['gender'] = df['gender'].replace({'Female':1,'Male':0})
    return df

Model Fitting¶

In [14]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder, MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

trainX, testX, trainY, y_test = train_test_split(df.drop('churn',axis=1),df['churn'],test_size=0.2,random_state=2)
In [15]:
X_num_train = trainX[num_cols]
X_cat_train = trainX['country']

scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaler.fit(X_num_train)

ohe = OneHotEncoder()
ohe.fit(X_cat_train.values.reshape(-1,1))

def data_transformer(X):
    X_num = X[num_cols]
    X_cat = X['country'].values.reshape(-1,1)
    
    X_num = scaler.transform(X_num)
    X_cat = ohe.transform(X_cat).toarray()
    return np.concatenate((X_num,X_cat),axis=1)

X_train = data_transformer(trainX)
X_test = data_transformer(testX)

y_train = trainY.values
y_test = y_test.values

Oversampling the Minority Class¶

In [24]:
traindf = pd.concat([trainX,trainY],axis=1)

n0, n1 = traindf['churn'].value_counts() #number of instances in each class

class0 = traindf[traindf['churn']==0]
class1 = traindf[traindf['churn']==1]
In [26]:
print("Before Resampling")
print("Fraction of Class 1: {}".format(n1/(n0+n1))) 
#We'll boost % of class 1 from 14% to ~40% of total
#taking 3*n1 samples gives ~44% of total

class1over = class1.sample(3*n1,replace=True) 
overdf = pd.concat([class0,class1over],axis=0).sample(frac=1)

print("After Resampling")
print("Fraction of Class 1: {}".format(overdf['churn'].value_counts()[1]/overdf.shape[0]))

Before Resampling
Fraction of Class 1: 0.20675
After Resampling
Fraction of Class 1: 0.4388043862752034

Tuning Select Models¶

In [33]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [34]:
def grid_search(model,param_grid,cv,X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test):
    gcv = GridSearchCV(model,param_grid,cv=cv,n_jobs=6,scoring='recall')
    gcv.fit(X_train,y_train)
    print("Model: %s"%model)
    y_pred_train = gcv.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test = gcv.predict(X_test)
    print("Test Accuracy Score: %s"%accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred_test))
    print("Test Recall Score: %s"%recall_score(y_test,y_pred_test))
    print()
    print("Train Accuracy Score: %s"%accuracy_score(y_train,y_pred_train))
    print("Train Recall Score: %s"%recall_score(y_train,y_pred_train))
    print("Optimized Model Parameters: ")
    print(gcv.best_params_)
    return gcv
